  "prompt": "What is the magnitude of the force applied by the body on an object due to law of inertia?",
  "response": "The force applied by a body on an object due to the law of inertia is not a direct force in the traditional sense. Instead, the law of inertia (Newton's First Law of Motion) describes the tendency of an object to resist changes to its state of motion.\n\nHere\u2019s how it works:\n\n1. **Law of Inertia**: An object will remain at rest or in uniform motion in a straight line unless acted upon by an external force.\n\n2. **Force Due to Inertia**: When a force is applied to accelerate or decelerate an object, the object resists this change due to its inertia. This resistance is not an applied force but rather a manifestation of the object's mass resisting acceleration (F = ma, where F is force, m is mass, and a is acceleration).\n\n3. **Reaction Force**: According to Newton's Third Law, when a body exerts a force on an object, the object exerts an equal and opposite force back on the body. However, this reaction force is not directly due to the law of inertia but rather the interaction between the body and the object.\n\nIn summary, the law of inertia does not directly cause a force to be applied by a body on an object. Instead, it explains why an object resists changes to its motion. The forces involved in such interactions are governed by Newton's Second and Third Laws of Motion.",
